It&#x27;s because they wanted to say both:<p><pre><code>    if (a) b;
</code></pre>
and<p><pre><code>   if (a) { b; c; }
</code></pre>
which tends to make you think of curly braces as a syntactic feature which can appear <i>anywhere</i>, turning many lines of code into one line of code. If you think that way then these should possibly also be valid:<p><pre><code>    {b; c}
    {b}
    {}
</code></pre>
but, since JS scope is function-oriented and in other places (e.g. functions) the braces are ultimately needed anyways, even for one-liners, it seems like this was a stupid choice and we should have just rejected the form:<p><pre><code>    if (a) b;
</code></pre>
and then the reuse of {} for lightweight (if non-robust) hashmaps would perhaps be unambiguous again.
